{
  "answer": "**In Cynewulf's *Juliana* (Chapter 1), the demon—bound and interrogated by the saint in her prison cell—confesses his role in tempting the first humans during his extended boast of evil deeds.**[^1]\n\nThe demon recounts his primordial temptation explicitly here:  \n> ...since first the heavens were raised and the stars set their course,  \n> the earth made fast **and the first people, Adam and Eve, from whom I tore life,  \n> and taught them to forsake the Lord’s love,  \n> His eternal grace, their bright, blessed home,  \n> so that misery became their lot for life,  \n> and for their children also, the darkest of deeds.**[^1]\n\nThis occurs after Juliana demands further confession of his crimes (*p-d3a506*), as part of his humiliated admission before she drags him publicly before the judge (*p-6b7e11*). No other passage in the poem attributes this specific claim to the demon.[^1]: /works/cynewulf-juliana-9a2157/01/translation/#p-15a5a2",
